[The lesions in the photo posted with the report (presumably from a case animal of this episode: http://www.seacoastonline.com/apps/pbcsi.dll/bilde?Site=SO&Date=20130912&Category=NEWS&ArtNo=309120392&Ref=AR&MaxW=570&MaxH=370&border=0) look like lymphoproliferative disease (LPDV) rather than poxvirus. LPDV (Retroviridae), a previously exotic virus to the United States, has been identified in wild turkeys (_Meleagris gallopavo_) since 2009. Lymphoproliferative disease is a rare disease of turkeys that emerged in Europe and Israel. It is noteworthy that turkeys (_Meleagris_ spp.) are originally from North America. This emergence in the old world suggests that the virus jumped species and adapted to a new host in domestic turkeys in the old world, and then it was introduced to North America, where it spread to the wild turkey population.

A picture of a turkey with typical lesions on its head can be accessed at http://www.outdoorlife.com/files/imagecache/photo-single/photo/1001321579/Turkey_virus.JPG. - Mod.PMB

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/613M.]
